{"id":"5db5a1c5-9d6a-48b3-b247-60a495fff764","testName":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","config":{"testName":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","protocol":"https","domain":"jsonplaceholder.typicode.com","testType":"load","steps":[{"name":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","method":"POST","path":"/posts","headers":[{"name":"Content-Type","value":"application/json"}],"body":"{\"title\": \"Load test\", \"body\": \"Testing LoadPilot performance\", \"userId\": 1}","assertions":{"expectedStatusCode":"201"}}],"load":{"users":5,"rampUpSeconds":5,"durationSeconds":30,"thinkTimeMs":1000},"performanceThresholds":{"goodMs":2000,"acceptableMs":5000}},"status":"completed","createdAt":"2026-07-07T19:16:12.906Z","dir":"C:\\Users\\Gunner\\loadpilot\\users\\peformance_toolkit_live\\jmeter-llm-toolkit-v7\\jmeter-llm-toolkit\\release\\data\\runs\\5db5a1c5-9d6a-48b3-b247-60a495fff764","logTail":["WARN StatusConsoleListener The use of package scanning to locate plugins is deprecated and will be removed in a future release","WARN StatusConsoleListener The use of package scanning to locate plugins is deprecated and will be removed in a future release","WARN StatusConsoleListener The use of package scanning to locate plugins is deprecated and will be removed in a future release","WARN StatusConsoleListener The use of package scanning to locate plugins is deprecated and will be removed in a future release","Creating summariser <summary>","Created the tree successfully using plan.jmx","Starting standalone test @ 2026 Jul 8 00:46:14 IST (1783451774802)","Waiting for possible Shutdown/StopTestNow/HeapDump/ThreadDump message on port 4445","summary +     48 in 00:00:15 =    3.1/s Avg:   329 Min:   248 Max:  1082 Err:     0 (0.00%) Active: 5 Started: 5 Finished: 0","summary +     56 in 00:00:15 =    3.7/s Avg:   316 Min:   266 Max:   497 Err:     0 (0.00%) Active: 0 Started: 5 Finished: 5","summary =    104 in 00:00:30 =    3.4/s Avg:   322 Min:   248 Max:  1082 Err:     0 (0.00%)","Tidying up ...    @ 2026 Jul 8 00:46:45 IST (1783451805108)","... end of run"],"_id":"f9aPQxcppgxNScPE","startedAt":"2026-07-07T19:16:12.908Z","jtlStats":[{"label":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","samples":104,"errors":0,"errorPct":0,"avgMs":323,"minMs":248,"maxMs":1082,"p90Ms":397,"p95Ms":497,"p99Ms":757,"throughputPerSec":3.58,"maxThreads":5,"errorBreakdown":[],"timeSeries":[{"t":0,"avgMs":893,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":2},{"t":1,"avgMs":424,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":2},{"t":2,"avgMs":395,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":4},{"t":4,"avgMs":357,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":5,"avgMs":279,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":6,"avgMs":268,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":4},{"t":7,"avgMs":275,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":3},{"t":8,"avgMs":285,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":10,"avgMs":257,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":11,"avgMs":281,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":12,"avgMs":329,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":4},{"t":13,"avgMs":302,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":15,"avgMs":294,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":16,"avgMs":294,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":17,"avgMs":288,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":4},{"t":18,"avgMs":295,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":19,"avgMs":292,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":21,"avgMs":280,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":22,"avgMs":318,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":23,"avgMs":403,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":4},{"t":24,"avgMs":427,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":3},{"t":25,"avgMs":364,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5},{"t":27,"avgMs":286,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":4},{"t":28,"avgMs":293,"errorCount":0,"sampleCount":5}],"performanceRating":"excellent","errorRating":"ok"}],"analysis":{"summary":"This test, labeled 'JSONPlaceholder Simple Test', involved sending 104 requests to a server and measuring how long it took for the server to respond, which is known as the response time. The average response time was 323 milliseconds, which is about as long as it takes to read a short sentence. The fastest response time was 248 milliseconds, and the slowest was 1082 milliseconds. The test also looked at the throughput, which is the number of requests the server can handle per second, and found it to be 3.58 requests per second. Since there were no errors, the error percentage was 0%, which is ideal. The performance rating for this test was 'excellent', based on the 95th percentile response time, or p95, being 497 milliseconds, which is below the threshold of 2000 milliseconds that was set for a 'good' rating. This means the server performed well under the given load. The test used a maximum of 5 concurrent threads, which are like virtual users making requests to the server at the same time. Given the low error rate and fast response times, the server handled the load well, indicating that it can handle a moderate number of users without significant performance issues.","bottlenecks":[{"label":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","observation":"The test showed no significant bottlenecks, with an average response time of 323 milliseconds and a p95 response time of 497 milliseconds, indicating that the server can handle the load without significant delays. The throughput of 3.58 requests per second was also relatively stable, suggesting that the server can process a moderate number of requests per second without issues.","likelyCause":"Given the low error rate and stable response times, it's likely that the server is properly configured and can handle the load without issues. However, without more data on the server's configuration and resources, it's difficult to pinpoint any potential causes for bottlenecks.","severity":"low"}],"recommendations":["To further improve the server's performance, consider increasing the number of concurrent threads to simulate a larger number of users, which would help identify any potential bottlenecks under heavier loads. This would help because it would put more stress on the server, allowing us to see how it performs when many users are making requests at the same time.","Monitor the server's resources, such as CPU and memory usage, to ensure that they are not being overutilized, which could cause performance issues. This is important because if the server runs out of resources, it won't be able to handle requests quickly, leading to slow response times and potentially even errors.","Consider implementing caching or other optimization techniques to reduce the load on the server and improve response times. This would help because caching allows the server to store frequently-used data in a way that's quick to access, reducing the time it takes to respond to requests.","Test the server under different load scenarios to ensure that it can handle a variety of conditions, such as sudden spikes in traffic or prolonged periods of high usage. This is important because it would help us understand how the server performs under different conditions, allowing us to identify and fix any potential issues before they cause problems in real-world use."]},"reviewFacts":{"threadGroups":[{"name":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test — Load","numThreads":5,"rampTime":5,"loops":-1}],"samplers":[{"name":"JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","hasAssertion":true,"hasExtractor":false}],"timers":1,"listeners":[{"name":"Failure Response Capture","enabled":true}],"csvDataSets":0,"suspiciousValues":[]},"review":{"issues":[{"severity":"low","scope":"plan-wide","issue":"The test plan has only one timer, which might not be sufficient to accurately simulate real user behavior. A timer in JMeter is used to introduce a pause between requests, mimicking how real users behave when interacting with a system, such as reading, thinking, or clicking. With only one timer, the test might not fully capture the natural flow of user interactions. However, since there is at least one timer, the test will have some level of realism in terms of pacing.","recommendation":"Consider adding more timers to the test plan to better simulate real user behavior. This will help ensure that the test results are more representative of actual usage patterns, which can lead to more accurate performance assessments."},{"severity":"low","scope":"sampler: JSONPlaceholder Simple Test","issue":"The sampler 'JSONPlaceholder Simple Test' has an assertion attached, which is good practice as it allows JMeter to verify if the response from the server is as expected. An assertion in JMeter is a check that decides whether a response counts as a 'pass' or 'fail'. However, it does not have an extractor, which is a component used to extract specific data from a response, such as a token or ID, for use in subsequent requests.","recommendation":"While not immediately necessary, consider adding an extractor if there's a need to capture and reuse data from the response in subsequent requests. This can enhance the test's ability to simulate complex user interactions that depend on previous responses."},{"severity":"medium","scope":"listener: Failure Response Capture","issue":"The listener 'Failure Response Capture' is enabled. A listener in JMeter is a component that processes the results of samplers, such as capturing and displaying the responses. However, some listeners, especially those that capture detailed response data, can be resource-intensive and may slow down the test or even cause it to fail under heavy load.","recommendation":"Consider disabling the 'Failure Response Capture' listener during load tests to prevent potential performance issues. It's useful for debugging purposes but might not be necessary during full-scale load testing. Instead, consider using less resource-intensive methods to capture failure responses, if needed."},{"severity":"low","scope":"plan-wide","issue":"There are no CSV Data Sets configured in the test plan. A CSV Data Set in JMeter is used to read data from a CSV file and parameterize the test, allowing for the simulation of multiple users or scenarios with different data. While not necessarily an issue, it means the test is not currently set up to easily scale to test different user scenarios or data-driven testing.","recommendation":"If the test needs to simulate multiple users or scenarios with varying data, consider adding a CSV Data Set. This can significantly enhance the test's flexibility and realism by allowing the test to parameterize user inputs or other variables."}],"summary":"The test plan appears to be generally well-structured with a reasonable configuration for simulating user load. It includes a thread group with a ramp-up time, indicating an understanding of how to simulate a gradual increase in user load. The presence of an assertion on the sampler is good practice for verifying response correctness. However, there are areas for improvement, such as potentially adding more timers to better simulate user pauses and considering the resource impact of enabled listeners during load tests. Additionally, the lack of CSV Data Sets might limit the test's ability to simulate diverse user scenarios. Overall, with a few adjustments, this test plan could provide more comprehensive and realistic performance assessments."},"usage":{"promptTokens":3231,"completionTokens":1468},"cost":0.003066,"finishedAt":"2026-07-07T19:16:53.106Z"}
